  "prompt": "Why are liquids not allowed on flights?",
  "response": "Liquids are restricted on flights primarily for security reasons. After the foiled terrorist plots in the early 2000s, specifically the 2006 transatlantic aircraft plot involving liquid explosives, aviation authorities implemented strict regulations on carrying liquids in carry-on baggage. The main reasons for these restrictions include:\n\n1. **Security Threats**: Terrorists can potentially use liquids to create explosives onboard. Limiting the amount of liquid passengers can carry reduces the risk of someone attempting to smuggle such materials onto an aircraft.\n\n2. **Screening Challenges**: Security screening processes at airports can more easily assess small quantities of certain types of liquids. Larger volumes might be harder to test effectively and could pose more significant challenges for detection systems.\n\n3. **Safety Concerns**: Even non-explosive liquids can pose safety risks on flights, such as spills or leaks that could damage aircraft systems or create hazardous conditions.\n\nBecause of these concerns, many countries enforce a \"3-1-1 rule\" for carry-on luggage: passengers can bring bottles of liquids, aerosols, and gels that are 3.4 ounces (100 milliliters) or smaller in a single quart-sized, clear, resealable bag. This helps mitigate the risks while allowing passengers to carry necessary liquids in limited amounts.",
